{
    "identity": "nprot-35",
    "title": "Hydrodynamics-based gene transduction",
    "content": [
        {
            "header": "Introduction",
            "content": "This highly efficient _in vivo_ gene transduction technique for laboratory mice was performed basically as described previously \\(_Gene Therapy_. 1999 Jul; **6\\(7)**:1258-1266). Hepatocytes are most effectively transduced by tail vein injection of a large volume of DNA solution in a short time. Practice with the injection technique is necessary\\!\\!\\!"
        },
        {
            "header": "Reagents",
            "content": "Reagents: \r\n\n\nSterile phosphate buffered saline \\(PBS), room temperature.\r\n\n\nExpression vector plasmid DNA."
        },
        {
            "header": "Equipment",
            "content": "3ml syringe.\r\n\n\n27-gauge needle.\r\n\n\nHeatlamp \\(Technilab Instruments, Pequannock, NJ).\r\n\n\nMouse holder, if necessary \\(Mouse Tail Illuminator, Braintree Scientific Inc., MA)."
        },
        {
            "header": "Procedure",
            "content": "1. Dilute the plasmid DNA with sterile PBS right before injection. The final concentration of the DNA should be calculated from the total amount of DNA/mouse.\r\n  2. Take 2 ml of the solution into a 3 ml syringe and put a 27-gauge needle to the syringe. Avoid any air bubbles in the syringe. \r\n  3. Warm up a mouse using a Heatlamp for 1-2 minutes. \r\n  4. Fix the mouse in a Mouse Tail Illuminator.\r\n  5. Inject the DNA solution from the tail vein in 5-7 seconds and put the mouse back into the cage. Mice may become less active transiently, but recover within 10 minutes."
        },
        {
            "header": "References",
            "content": "Liu F, Song Y and Liu D. _Gene Therapy_. 1999 Jul; **6\\(7)**:1258-1266"
        }
    ],
